  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of essential and quality primary health care services, including sexual and reproductive health care for vulnerable conflict-affected population in Zabul Province.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed action will address the health humanitarian needs of the conflict-affected population in Zabul Province, through the provision of primary health care services in Qalat and Shajoy districts. This action aims at improving access to basic primary health care (PHC), including sexual reproductive health (SRH) and COVID-19 specific support. 
In Qalat district, INTERSOS will focus particularly on supporting the Sexual and Reproductive Health services provided at Qalat temporary Provincial Hospital, while also improving the quality of outpatient department (OPD) consultations through the provision of additional space, medical equipment, drugs and human resources. 25.615 vulnerable individuals will benefit from this intervention. The project will: 

1) support the provision of OPD consultations within Qalat temporary Provincial Hospital, through specialized medical personnel (medical doctors, nurses and midwives) expansion of space for consultations provision of proper medical equipment and drugs. 
2) provision of primary health care services in hard to reach areas of Shajoy district through the deployment of a health team.

3) provision of personal protective equipment for medical personnel deployed in Qalat and Shajoy districts in order to prevent the further spread of COVID-19. 
INTERSOS will implement this project in synergy with ongoing actions within the same area. Particularly, a referral system will be put in place to the Family Protection Center (FPC) embedded in the Qalat Provincial Hospital.    
Through its comprehensive intervention, INTERSOS will address rising COVID-19 pandemic needs with prevention, preparedness and response integrated activities of Infection and Prevention Control (IPC), focused hygiene promotion and capacity building for front-line health workers.</narrative>
  </description>
